rkney  (  d. 1116 ), to whom Kirkwall cathedral is dedicated. The name was imported to Scotland and Ireland during the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Mànas","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of   Magnus ."]}]},{"name":"Nilsson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lars, Nils, Per, Anders, Egil, Lennart, Sven, Birgit, Fredrik, Sten, Algot.  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Gerhard, Gotthard, Karl-Heinz.","Swedish and German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Nils</i>, a shortened form of <i>Nikolaus</i>. Compare   Nilson  ,   Neilson   3, and   Nielson   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Nilson","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated in the Middle Ages as either a patronymic from   Neil   or a metronymic from   Nell .  Use as a given name probably began as a tribute to the British admiral  Lord Nelson  (  1758–1805 ), the victor of the Battle of Trafalgar;  see also  Horatio .  It is, however, now much more common in the United States than in Britain, its popularity there in the 1930s and 40s no doubt having been influenced by the American film actor and singer  Nelson Eddy  (  1901–67 ). Nowadays the name is universally associated with the South African statesman  Nelson Mandela  (  b. 1918 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Magnus Nilsson had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Magnus Nilsson i Tovaryd."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1300":"1300","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Sverige":"Rootsi"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1300":"1300","about 1300":"noin 1300","Sverige":"Ruotsi"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1300":"1300","about 1300":"environ 1300","Sverige":"Suède","lifeSummary":"Mrs Magnus Nilsson a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Magnus Nilsson i Tovaryd."},"de":{"–":"Ve